Headlines.Author: Nicole Bullock
Headlines.Headline: SmartMoney(8/1) Street Smart: A Better Measure

PARAGRAPH.#text: Miles or kilometers? Hagstrom's or MapQuest? As the debate over the best way to measure from here to there continues to evolve, investors and analysts have a similar task in the stock market. Take growth, for example. Earnings per share is the mainstay of Wall Street's approach to gauging a company's growth and the value of its shares on any given day. Another school of thought argues for a metric that digs deeper than the bottom line. "Investors face the crucial task of distinguishing good and bad growth," says Michael Mauboussin, chief investment strategist at Legg Mason Capital Management. One way to do that is to look at not just how much a company is growing but also how much it costs the company to produce that growth.
